                        <H3 style=" font-style: underline">1. <u>Differentiate Between Friendly Banter and Bullying:
                        </u>
                        </H3>
                        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                            Little arguments and quarrels are common occurrences between friends. Most friends argue or tease one another. That is fine as long as it is done in the right spirit and not to hurt someone’s feelings. However, in some instances, arguments can take unexpected turns and can end up in one person bullying the other. It is important to differentiate bullying from friendly banter. A few instances that classify as bullying include:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ul style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';"><li>●	Gain a Realistic Perspective on Self-Love </li>
                              <li>● Passing comments based on a person’s physical appearance or weaknesses </li>
                              <li>●	Derogatory name-calling </li>
                              <li>●	Using abusive or curse words </li>
                              <li>●	Humiliating someone or pulling them down </li>
                              <li>●	Mocking people</li>
                              <li>●	Raising hands and getting physically violent  </li>
                              <li>●	Any behaviour that makes a person uncomfortable </li>
                             
                              
                              
                                  </ul> 
                              
                          </p>
                        <H3 style=" font-style: underline">2. <u>Understand the Nature of Bullying:
                        </u>
                        </H3>
                        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                            Once you have understood that you or someone in your surroundings is being bullied, the next step is to identify the nature and severity of the bullying. Examine whether the bully is resorting to verbal forms of bullying like mocking, passing comments or using abusive language or using physical violence as well. Take action in accordance with the nature and severity of the bully’s behaviour. Initial phases of verbal bullying, like teasing can be dealt with by talking to the bully and sorting the issue. However, more physical and violent forms of bullying need strict and immediate action and must be reported at the earliest. 

                        </p>
                   
                        <div class="row" >
                            <div class="col-lg-12 col-12" style="padding: 0 0 0 0;" >
                                <img alt="Boy and girl bulling other girl" class="blogimg" src="https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/waves-36bb5.appspot.com/o/How%20to%20Confront%20Bullying%3F%2F4029055.jpg?alt=media&token=28982f6a-5564-4cd8-b94f-b2fe026a56d3" >
                            </div>
                            </div>   

                            <H3 style=" font-style: underline">3. <u> Address the Issue by Talking to the Perpetrator:
                            </u>
                            </H3>
                            
                            <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                                Sometimes, the person bullying you or another individual may be unaware that their actions make someone uncomfortable, and they continue with the same behaviour. In such cases, it is crucial to address the issue by talking to the person privately and letting them know their behaviour is making others uncomfortable. It’s great if the person understands and is willing to rectify their mistakes and apologise to the person they hurt. 
                            </p>
                            <div class="row" >
                                <div class="col-lg-12 col-12" style="padding: 0 0 0 0;" >
                                    <img alt="Myths vs facts about menstruation" class="blogimg" src="https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/waves-36bb5.appspot.com/o/The%20Importance%20of%20Destigmatising%20Menstruation%2F61Z_2112.w009.n001.65B.p14.65.jpg?alt=media&token=17558810-44b2-4bdb-8b44-a13ec8508be0" >
                                </div>
                                </div> 
                            <H3 style=" font-style: underline">4. <u>Confront the Perpetrator in Other’s Presence:
                            </u>
                            </H3>
                            <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                                If the person does not admit their mistake and continues bullying and troubling you or others, you must confront the person in other people’s presence to catch the person off-guard. When you highlight their inappropriate behaviour in front of others, it will add social pressure on the person since they are being called out in public. You would also have several eyewitnesses who could support you in confronting the bully. 
                            </p>
                            <div class="row" >
                                <div class="col-lg-12 col-12" style="padding: 0 0 0 0;" >
                                    <img alt="School students enjoying together" class="blogimg" src="https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/waves-36bb5.appspot.com/o/How%20to%20Confront%20Bullying%3F%2F4293766.jpg?alt=media&token=18763603-c9d2-4b09-b504-608333c36a24" >
                                </div>
                                </div> 
  <br>
                            <H3 style=" font-style: underline">5. <u>Garner Support from Friends:
                            </u>
                            </H3>
                            <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                                Confronting people alone can be daunting and intimidating. Therefore, you can garner support from your friends and ask them to accompany you for the right cause. Whether you are being bullied or someone else, you can confront the bully in a group. Having people by your side who can support you and question the person’s immoral acts will have a greater effect on stopping the person from continuing with the same behaviour. 
  </p>

                                <H3 style=" font-style: underline">6. <u>Note Down the Instances of Bullying:
                                </u>
                                </H3>
                                <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                                    Whenever you encounter yourself or someone else being bullied, don’t turn an ignorant eye toward the situation. Note the details of each incident and remember the words and actions of the bully and what impact they had on the victim. Remember the place, the date and what triggered the situation to escalate. Noting such details would help you be an informed eyewitness so that you can provide sufficient evidence against the perpetrator when needed. 
                                </p>
                                <div class="row" >
                                    <div class="col-lg-12 col-12" style="padding: 0 0 0 0;" >
                                        <img alt="Student bullying each other poster" class="blogimg" src="https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/waves-36bb5.appspot.com/o/How%20to%20Confront%20Bullying%3F%2Fkids_boy_girl_agression.jpg?alt=media&token=26daf563-6717-4269-bb62-bbecf38eba32" >
                                    </div>
                                    </div>
                                <H3 style=" font-style: underline">7. <u>Subtly Extend a Helping Hand to a Victim:
                                </u>
                                
      <br>
                                </H3>
                                <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                                    Whenever you observe someone around you being bullied or feeling uncomfortable, approach them and subtly drop hints asking if they need help. Asking the victim if they need help in front of the bully would put them on the spot. Instead, you can walk over to the victim and say, “Hi! How are you doing?” and hug them. While hugging them, whisper and ask if they need help. If they say yes, come up with an excuse like “I need your help finding my math notebook” and take them out of the situation along with you.   </p>
                                
                                </p>
                               
                                    <H3 style=" font-style: underline">8. <u>Give Neutral Responses to Taunts:
                                </u>
                                </H3>
                                <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                                    When someone taunts you in an attempt to bully you, the best response is to keep silent and ignore them. Though continuous taunts can be frustrating, you must understand that the bully intends to elicit a response from you. The more frustratingly you respond, the more they will continue to bully you. Being neutral and showing that their words don’t matter to you will discourage them from bullying you. However, if the person’s actions exceed an acceptable limit, you must raise your voice and not remain silent. 
  </p>
  <div class="row" >
    <div class="col-lg-12 col-12" style="padding: 0 0 0 0;" >
        <img alt="Students getting angry on each other" class="blogimg" src="https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/waves-36bb5.appspot.com/o/How%20to%20Confront%20Bullying%3F%2F4010544.jpg?alt=media&token=74be7f9b-ecb6-49c1-9dec-965fa6747b5b" >
    </div>
    </div>
    
  <H3 style=" font-style: underline">9. <u>Inform your Parents and a Teacher:
</u>
</H3>
<p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
    Informing adults about such situations is extremely important since you will need adult intervention to control and prevent such behaviour from occurring. So, tell your parents if you are being bullied by someone and don’t hide it from them. They will help you approach the school authorities and take action. Moreover, keep a trusted teacher informed if you or anyone else is being bullied and ask for their help in controlling the situation. 
</p>

<H3 style=" font-style: underline">10. <u>Report Any Form of Violence Immediately:
</u>
</H3>
<p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
    Minor instances like taunting and comments can be handled through ignorance. But when teasing or humiliation takes violent forms, they must be reported immediately. Not just physical violence but verbal violence in the form of derogatory abuses, yelling, and shouting must be reported to school authorities or adults immediately. 
    <div class="row" >
        <div class="col-lg-12 col-12" style="padding: 0 0 0 0;" >
            <img alt="bullying poster" class="blogimg" src="https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/waves-36bb5.appspot.com/o/How%20to%20Confront%20Bullying%3F%2F4015513.jpg?alt=media&token=ac7abb7a-534f-4a4a-b776-cd05ac9ae3ee" >
        </div>
        </div>

        <H3 style=" font-style: underline">11. <u>Form Anti-Bullying Committees:
        </u>
        </H3>
        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
            All schools must have anti-bullying committees where students can report any instances of bullying or violence and get it addressed at the earliest. Talk to your classmates and approach your teachers to help you form such a committee if your school doesn’t already have one. You can hold regular meetings under this committee to check any bullying cases and address them sensibly. 
        </p>
        




